      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(memory): add EPERM fallback for atomic reindex",
        "body": "Fixes #78640\n\n## Summary\n\nWhat problem does this PR solve?\n\nMemory atomic reindex could still fail on Windows after exhausting the existing `EPERM` rename retry loop, leaving `openclaw memory index --force` unable to replace the sqlite index files.\n\nWhy does this matter now?\n\nIssue #78640 reports that retrying `fs.rename` is not enough for persistent Windows `EPERM` failures during the memory index swap. The failed swap blocks forced memory reindexing for affected users.\n\nWhat is the intended outcome?\n\nAfter the bounded retry loop is exhausted for `EPERM`, the atomic reindex move path falls back to `copyFile` followed by `unlink` for the sqlite file and optional `-wal`/`-shm` sidecars.\n\nWhat should reviewers focus on?\n\n- The exhausted-`EPERM` fallback in `extensions/memory-core/src/memory/manager-atomic-reindex.ts`.\n- The deterministic persistent-`EPERM` regression in `extensions/memory-core/src/memory/manager.atomic-reindex.test.ts`.\n\n## Linked context\n\nWhich issue does this close?\n\nCloses #78640.\n\nWas this requested by a maintainer or owner?\n\nNo direct maintainer request beyond the open issue classification.\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: memory atomic reindex no longer throws after a persistent `EPERM` from `rename`; once configured attempts are exhausted, the move path copies the source index file to the target and unlinks the source.\n- Real environment tested: local OpenClaw contributor checkout `/Users/andy/openclaw-78640` on branch `fix/memory-atomic-reindex-eperm-78640`, macOS, Node/Vitest through the repo's `pnpm exec vitest` wrapper. The proof uses the production `moveMemoryIndexFiles` implementation with injected file operations.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch: ran the focused atomic reindex test file with `pnpm exec vitest run extensions/memory-core/src/memory/manager.atomic-reindex.test.ts`.\n- Evidence after fix (copied terminal output):\n\n```text\nRUN  v4.1.7 /Users/andy/openclaw-78640\n\nTest Files  1 passed (1)\n     Tests  13 passed (13)\n  Start at  00:22:47\n  Duration  347ms (transform 265ms, setup 208ms, import 8ms, tests 57ms, environment 0ms)\n```\n\n- Observed result after fix: the new regression injects persistent `EPERM` for every rename attempt, verifies 9 total rename attempts across the base sqlite file plus `-wal` and `-shm`, then verifies fallback `copyFile` and `unlink` calls for each source/target pair.\n- What was not tested: no Windows VM was used; this is deterministic source-level proof of the Windows failure mode by injecting persistent `EPERM` into the production move helper.\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints: the test does not exercise Windows kernel file-handle behavior directly, but it proves the code path taken after the exact persistent `EPERM` error reported in the issue.\n- Before evidence (optional but encouraged): before this patch, the same persistent `EPERM` path would exhaust the rename attempts and throw the original `EPERM` instead of copying and unlinking the index files.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nWhich commands did you run?\n\n- `pnpm exec vitest run extensions/memory-core/src/memory/manager.atomic-reindex.test.ts`\n- `pnpm exec oxfmt --check --threads=1 extensions/memory-core/src/memory/manager-atomic-reindex.ts extensions/memory-core/src/memory/manager.atomic-reindex.test.ts`\n- `pnpm tsgo:test:extensions`\n- `pnpm exec oxlint --tsconfig config/tsconfig/oxlint.extensions.json extensions/memory-core/src/memory/manager-atomic-reindex.ts extensions/memory-core/src/memory/manager.atomic-reindex.test.ts`\n- `git diff --check`\n- `git log --format='%h %an <%ae> %s' upstream/main..HEAD`\n\nWhat regression coverage was added or updated?\n\nAdded a deterministic unit regression that forces persistent `EPERM` from rename and asserts the fallback copies and unlinks the base sqlite file plus `-wal`/`-shm` sidecars.\n\nWhat failed before this fix, if known?\n\nWith persistent `EPERM`, `renameWithRetry` exhausted the retry limit and threw instead of falling back to copy/unlink.\n\nIf no test was added, why not?\n\nA focused regression test was added.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nYes.\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nNo.\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nNo.\n\nWhat is the highest-risk area?\n\nIndex swap behavior when rename fails for reasons other than the reported persistent Windows `EPERM`.\n\nHow is that risk mitigated?\n\nThe fallback only runs for `EPERM` after the existing bounded retry loop is exhausted; `ENOENT`, non-transient errors, and non-`EPERM` transient exhaustion keep their previous behavior.\n\n## Current review state\n\nWhat is the next action?\n\nReady for maintainer and ClawSweeper review.\n\nWhat is still waiting on author, maintainer, CI, or external proof?\n\nWaiting on GitHub CI and ClawSweeper review. A Windows VM proof was not run because the requested deterministic persistent-`EPERM` unit proof covers the failure path without requiring real Windows infrastructure.\n\n@clawsweeper please re-review.\n",
